{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"24ed06ec-c309-46bc-a634-06b357f28e95","content":"Run **`dotnet workload update`**. Here's the difference:\n\n- **`dotnet workload update`** — downloads and installs the latest versions of all installed workloads to match your current SDK. After an SDK update, this is what brings workloads (like `maui`) back in sync.\n\n- **`dotnet workload repair`** — reinstalls the *same versions* already recorded. It fixes corrupted or missing files but won't pull newer versions needed by a newer SDK.\n\n**TL;DR:** Your workloads are outdated relative to the new SDK, so `update` is the right choice:\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload update\n```\n\nIf builds still fail after that, try `dotnet workload restore` from your project directory — it will install any workloads declared in your project file.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"42e37773-d982-4a64-a663-387be56b8310","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about the difference between `dotnet workload update` and `dotnet workload repair` for fixing build issues after a .NET SDK update. This is a general knowledge question — I don't need to look at any files or run any commands.","outputTokens":258,"requestId":"044F:B86C3:A8C8BD:C11AE2:6A02791B"},"id":"2e504124-2011-42f5-bfff-245e229b0e05","timestamp":"2026-05-12T00:49:38.367Z","parentId":"92b62454-94ac-401a-a970-68a2054c8171"}
